<!-- FCF Quality Checklist -->
<div class="content-section">
  <h2>FCF Quality Checklist</h2>
  <p>Use these four criteria to quickly assess whether a company's free cash flow profile signals financial strength.</p>

  <div class="checklist-grid">
    <div class="checklist-item">
      <div class="checklist-icon">✅</div>
      <div class="checklist-text"><strong>Positive FCF</strong> — The company generates more cash from operations than it spends on capital expenditures. Consistent positive FCF over 5+ years is a strong sign of a durable business.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="checklist-item">
      <div class="checklist-icon">✅</div>
      <div class="checklist-text"><strong>FCF &gt; Net Income</strong> — When free cash flow exceeds net income, earnings quality is high. This means the company converts its profits into actual cash rather than paper gains.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="checklist-item">
      <div class="checklist-icon">✅</div>
      <div class="checklist-text"><strong>Consistent FCF Growth</strong> — Growing free cash flow year over year shows improving operational efficiency and pricing power. A 10%+ CAGR in FCF over 5 years is excellent.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="checklist-item">
      <div class="checklist-icon">✅</div>
      <div class="checklist-text"><strong>Low CapEx-to-OCF Ratio</strong> — A CapEx/OCF ratio below 30% means the company keeps most of its operating cash flow as free cash flow. Asset-light businesses typically excel here.</div>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<!-- Key Insights -->
<div class="content-section">
  <h2>5 Key Insights About Free Cash Flow</h2>

  <div class="insights-grid">
    <div class="insight-card">
      <div class="insight-num">1</div>
      <div class="insight-text"><strong>FCF is the ultimate reality check.</strong> A company can report rising earnings for years while free cash flow declines — a warning sign of accounting aggression. Always verify that reported profits translate into actual cash generation.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="insight-card">
      <div class="insight-num">2</div>
      <div class="insight-text"><strong>Negative FCF is not always bad.</strong> High-growth companies like Amazon or Tesla had years of negative FCF while investing heavily in capacity. The key question: is the company investing for future returns, or failing to generate cash from a mature business?</div>
    </div>
    <div class="insight-card">
      <div class="insight-num">3</div>
      <div class="insight-text"><strong>FCF yield is the cash-based P/E ratio.</strong> An FCF yield of 7% means you're buying $7 of annual cash flow for every $100 invested. Compare this to bond yields — if FCF yield exceeds the 10-year Treasury rate, the stock may offer better value.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="insight-card">
      <div class="insight-num">4</div>
      <div class="insight-text"><strong>Sector differences matter enormously.</strong> Tech companies routinely convert 25-35% of revenue to FCF. Utilities and industrials may convert only 5-10%. Always compare FCF margins within the same sector, never across different industries.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="insight-card">
      <div class="insight-num">5</div>
      <div class="insight-text"><strong>Buybacks + dividends should not exceed FCF.</strong> When a company pays out more than its free cash flow in shareholder returns, it must borrow or sell assets to fund the difference — an unsustainable practice that erodes long-term value.</div>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<!-- FAQ Section -->
<div class="faq-section">
  <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

  <div class="faq-item">
    <div class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
      <span>What is free cash flow and why does it matter?</span>
      <span class="faq-arrow">▼</span>
    </div>
    <div class="faq-a">Free cash flow (FCF) is the cash a company generates after accounting for capital expenditures needed to maintain or expand its asset base. FCF = Operating Cash Flow - Capital Expenditures. It matters because it represents the actual cash available for dividends, share buybacks, debt repayment, and acquisitions — making it the most reliable measure of a company's financial health.</div>
  </div>

  <div class="faq-item">
    <div class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
      <span>How do you calculate free cash flow?</span>
      <span class="faq-arrow">▼</span>
    </div>
    <div class="faq-a">The most common free cash flow formula is: FCF = Operating Cash Flow - Capital Expenditures. You can also calculate it from net income: FCF = Net Income + Depreciation & Amortization - Changes in Working Capital - Capital Expenditures. Both methods should produce similar results when using consistent financial data from the cash flow statement.</div>
  </div>

  <div class="faq-item">
    <div class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
      <span>What is a good FCF yield for stocks?</span>
      <span class="faq-arrow">▼</span>
    </div>
    <div class="faq-a">An FCF yield above 5% is generally considered attractive for value investors. FCF yield between 3-5% is average for the S&P 500, while yields above 8% may indicate undervaluation or a mature company returning significant cash. Growth stocks often have lower FCF yields (1-3%) because they reinvest heavily. Always compare FCF yield within the same sector.</div>
  </div>

  <div class="faq-item">
    <div class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
      <span>What is the difference between free cash flow and net income?</span>
      <span class="faq-arrow">▼</span>
    </div>
    <div class="faq-a">Net income includes non-cash charges like depreciation and can be manipulated through accounting choices. Free cash flow measures actual cash generated, making it harder to distort. A company can report positive net income while burning cash (negative FCF), which is a red flag. Conversely, a company with negative net income but positive FCF may be healthier than it appears.</div>
  </div>

  <div class="faq-item">
    <div class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
      <span>What is free cash flow to equity (FCFE)?</span>
      <span class="faq-arrow">▼</span>
    </div>
    <div class="faq-a">Free Cash Flow to Equity (FCFE) is the cash available specifically to equity shareholders after all expenses, reinvestment, and debt obligations. FCFE = FCF + Net Borrowing - Debt Repayment. It is used in equity valuation models like the FCFE discount model to estimate the intrinsic value of a company's stock.</div>
  </div>
</div>

<script is:inline src="https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/npm/chart.js"></script>

<script is:inline>
  function fmt(n) {
    if (Math.abs(n) >= 1e9) return "$" + (n / 1e9).toFixed(2) + "B";
    if (Math.abs(n) >= 1e6) return "$" + (n / 1e6).toFixed(2) + "M";
    if (Math.abs(n) >= 1e3) return "$" + (n / 1e3).toFixed(1) + "K";
    return "$" + n.toFixed(2);
  }

  function pct(n) { return n.toFixed(2) + "%"; }

  function gv(id) { return parseFloat(document.getElementById(id).value) || 0; }

  function showResult(id, rows) {
    var box = document.getElementById(id);
    var html = "";
    for (var r = 0; r < rows.length; r++) {
      var cls = "";
      if (rows[r].color === "pos") cls = " pos";
      if (rows[r].color === "neg") cls = " neg";
      html += '<div class="result-row"><span class="result-label">' + rows[r].label + '</span><span class="result-val' + cls + '">' + rows[r].value + '</span></div>';
    }
    box.innerHTML = html;
    box.style.display = "block";
  }

  /* Direct FCF Calculator */
  function calcDirect() {
    var ocf = gv("d-ocf");
    var capex = gv("d-capex");
    var fcf = ocf - capex;
    var capexRatio = ocf > 0 ? (capex / ocf) * 100 : 0;
    var rows = [
      { label: "Operating Cash Flow", value: fmt(ocf) },
      { label: "Capital Expenditures", value: fmt(capex), color: "neg" },
      { label: "Free Cash Flow", value: fmt(fcf), color: fcf >= 0 ? "pos" : "neg" },
      { label: "CapEx / OCF Ratio", value: pct(capexRatio), color: capexRatio < 30 ? "pos" : "neg" }
    ];
    showResult("d-result", rows);
  }

  /* Indirect FCF Calculator */
  function calcIndirect() {
    var ni = gv("i-ni");
    var da = gv("i-da");
    var wc = gv("i-wc");
    var capex = gv("i-capex");
    var ocf = ni + da - wc;
    var fcf = ocf - capex;
    var rows = [
      { label: "Net Income", value: fmt(ni) },
      { label: "Add: D&A", value: "+" + fmt(da) },
      { label: "Less: ΔWorking Capital", value: "-" + fmt(wc) },
      { label: "Operating Cash Flow", value: fmt(ocf) },
      { label: "Less: CapEx", value: "-" + fmt(capex), color: "neg" },
      { label: "Free Cash Flow", value: fmt(fcf), color: fcf >= 0 ? "pos" : "neg" }
    ];
    if (ni > 0) {
      var conversion = (fcf / ni) * 100;
      rows.push({ label: "FCF / Net Income", value: pct(conversion), color: conversion > 100 ? "pos" : "neg" });
    }
    showResult("i-result", rows);
  }

  /* Alternative FCF from Revenue */
  function calcAlt() {
    var rev = gv("alt-rev");
    var margin = gv("alt-margin") / 100;
    var da = gv("alt-da");
    var capex = gv("alt-capex");
    var tax = gv("alt-tax") / 100;
    var wc = gv("alt-wc");
    var ebit = rev * margin;
    var nopat = ebit * (1 - tax);
    var fcf = nopat + da - capex - wc;
    var fcfMargin = rev > 0 ? (fcf / rev) * 100 : 0;
    var rows = [
      { label: "Revenue", value: fmt(rev) },
      { label: "EBIT (Rev × Margin)", value: fmt(ebit) },
      { label: "NOPAT (EBIT × (1 - Tax))", value: fmt(nopat) },
      { label: "Add: D&A", value: "+" + fmt(da) },
      { label: "Less: CapEx", value: "-" + fmt(capex), color: "neg" },
      { label: "Less: ΔWorking Capital", value: "-" + fmt(wc) },
      { label: "Free Cash Flow", value: fmt(fcf), color: fcf >= 0 ? "pos" : "neg" },
      { label: "FCF Margin", value: pct(fcfMargin), color: fcfMargin > 10 ? "pos" : "neg" }
    ];
    showResult("alt-result", rows);
  }

  /* FCF Yield Calculator */
  function calcYield() {
    var fcfps = gv("fy-fcfps");
    var price = gv("fy-price");
    var yld = price > 0 ? (fcfps / price) * 100 : 0;
    var ptofcf = fcfps > 0 ? price / fcfps : 0;
    var rows = [
      { label: "FCF per Share", value: fmt(fcfps) },
      { label: "Stock Price", value: fmt(price) },
      { label: "FCF Yield", value: pct(yld), color: yld >= 5 ? "pos" : (yld >= 3 ? "" : "neg") },
      { label: "Price / FCF", value: ptofcf.toFixed(1) + "x" }
    ];
    showResult("fy-result", rows);
    var interp = document.getElementById("fy-interp");
    if (!interp) {
      interp = document.createElement("div");
      interp.id = "fy-interp";
      interp.className = "interpretation";
      document.getElementById("fy-result").appendChild(interp);
    }
    if (yld >= 8) {
      interp.style.background = "rgba(16,185,129,0.15)";
      interp.style.color = "#10b981";
      interp.textContent = "High FCF yield — potentially undervalued or a mature cash cow";
    } else if (yld >= 5) {
      interp.style.background = "rgba(16,185,129,0.10)";
      interp.style.color = "#10b981";
      interp.textContent = "Attractive FCF yield — strong cash generation relative to price";
    } else if (yld >= 3) {
      interp.style.background = "rgba(245,158,11,0.15)";
      interp.style.color = "#f59e0b";
      interp.textContent = "Average FCF yield — in line with S&P 500 median";
    } else if (yld > 0) {
      interp.style.background = "rgba(239,68,68,0.15)";
      interp.style.color = "#ef4444";
      interp.textContent = "Low FCF yield — priced for growth or limited cash generation";
    } else {
      interp.style.background = "rgba(239,68,68,0.15)";
      interp.style.color = "#ef4444";
      interp.textContent = "Negative or zero FCF — company is not generating free cash";
    }
    interp.style.display = "block";
  }

  /* FCFE Calculator */
  function calcFCFE() {
    var fcf = gv("fe-fcf");
    var borrow = gv("fe-borrow");
    var repay = gv("fe-repay");
    var fcfe = fcf + borrow - repay;
    var netDebt = borrow - repay;
    var rows = [
      { label: "Free Cash Flow", value: fmt(fcf) },
      { label: "Add: Net Borrowing", value: "+" + fmt(borrow) },
      { label: "Less: Debt Repayment", value: "-" + fmt(repay), color: "neg" },
      { label: "Net Debt Impact", value: fmt(netDebt), color: netDebt >= 0 ? "pos" : "neg" },
      { label: "FCFE", value: fmt(fcfe), color: fcfe >= 0 ? "pos" : "neg" }
    ];
    showResult("fe-result", rows);
  }

  /* FAQ Toggle */
  function toggleFaq(el) {
    var item = el.parentElement;
    var isOpen = item.className.indexOf("open") !== -1;
    if (isOpen) {
      item.className = "faq-item";
    } else {
      item.className = "faq-item open";
    }
  }

  /* Charts */
  document.addEventListener("DOMContentLoaded", function() {
    /* Waterfall Chart */
    var wCtx = document.getElementById("waterfallChart");
    if (wCtx) {
      var ocf = 12.5;
      var capex = -3.2;
      var fcfVal = ocf + capex;
      var divs = -1.8;
      var buybacks = -2.5;
      var remaining = fcfVal + divs + buybacks;

      new Chart(wCtx, {
        type: "bar",
        data: {
          labels: ["Operating\nCash Flow", "CapEx", "Free Cash\nFlow", "Dividends", "Buybacks", "Remaining\nCash"],
          datasets: [
            {
              label: "Invisible Base",
              data: [0, ocf + capex, 0, fcfVal + divs + buybacks < 0 ? fcfVal + divs : fcfVal, fcfVal + divs, remaining < 0 ? 0 : 0],
              backgroundColor: "transparent",
              borderWidth: 0
            },
            {
              label: "Increase",
              data: [ocf, 0, fcfVal, 0, 0, remaining > 0 ? remaining : 0],
              backgroundColor: ["#10b981", "transparent", "#10b981", "transparent", "transparent", "#4a8fe7"],
              borderRadius: 4
            },
            {
              label: "Decrease",
              data: [0, Math.abs(capex), 0, Math.abs(divs), Math.abs(buybacks), remaining < 0 ? Math.abs(remaining) : 0],
              backgroundColor: ["transparent", "#ef4444", "transparent", "#f59e0b", "#f59e0b", "#ef4444"],
              borderRadius: 4
            }
          ]
        },
        options: {
          responsive: true,
          maintainAspectRatio: true,
          plugins: {
            legend: { display: false },
            tooltip: {
              callbacks: {
                label: function(ctx) {
                  if (ctx.datasetIndex === 0) return "";
                  return "$" + ctx.raw.toFixed(1) + "B";
                }
              }
            }
          },
          scales: {
            x: {
              stacked: true,
              grid: { display: false },
              ticks: { color: "#8b949e", font: { size: 11 } }
            },
            y: {
              stacked: true,
              grid: { color: "rgba(48,54,61,0.5)" },
              ticks: {
                color: "#8b949e",
                callback: function(v) { return "$" + v + "B"; }
              }
            }
          }
        }
      });
    }

    /* Sector FCF Yield Chart */
    var sCtx = document.getElementById("sectorChart");
    if (sCtx) {
      var sectors = ["Energy", "Financials", "Healthcare", "Industrials", "Consumer Staples", "Materials", "Utilities", "Communication", "Consumer Disc.", "Real Estate", "Technology"];
      var yields = [8.2, 6.5, 5.4, 5.0, 4.8, 4.5, 4.2, 3.9, 3.6, 3.2, 3.8];
      var colors = yields.map(function(y) {
        if (y >= 6) return "#10b981";
        if (y >= 4.5) return "#4a8fe7";
        return "#f59e0b";
      });

      new Chart(sCtx, {
        type: "bar",
        data: {
          labels: sectors,
          datasets: [{
            label: "FCF Yield %",
            data: yields,
            backgroundColor: colors,
            borderRadius: 4
          }]
        },
        options: {
          indexAxis: "y",
          responsive: true,
          maintainAspectRatio: true,
          plugins: {
            legend: { display: false },
            tooltip: {
              callbacks: {
                label: function(ctx) { return ctx.raw.toFixed(1) + "% FCF Yield"; }
              }
            }
          },
          scales: {
            x: {
              grid: { color: "rgba(48,54,61,0.5)" },
              ticks: {
                color: "#8b949e",
                callback: function(v) { return v + "%"; }
              }
            },
            y: {
              grid: { display: false },
              ticks: { color: "#8b949e", font: { size: 11 } }
            }
          }
        }
      });
    }
  });
</script>

</SiteLayout>
